<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName authorityName="K. Hori &amp; H. Kanemitsu" authorityYear="2021" class="Polypodiopsida" family="Athyriaceae" genus="Diplazium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Diplazium kanayamaense" order="Polypodiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" phylum="Pteridophyta" rank="species" species="kanayamaense">
Diplazium 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
kanayamaense
</taxonomicName>
has been identified to be from Kyushu, western Japan (Figures 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Diplazium x kanayamaense K. Hori &amp; H. Kanemitsu A lower stipe scale B habit C detail of abaxial pinnule A-C from the holotype (KAG 151589 (illustration by K. Hori)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.172.60660.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/504158" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">3</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Map showing the known distribution in Japan of D. x kanayamaense = Red circle and D. x tsukushiense = Blue circle." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.172.60660.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/504160" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">5</figureCitation>
). The species is observed on soil under semi-evergreen forest near streams. This hybrid is endemic to Japan and exists in a population of approximately 124 individuals with juveniles, although parents, 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. chinense" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="chinense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">D. chinense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. deciduum" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="deciduum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">D. deciduum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were both absent near its side.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="39" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="39">IUCN Red List Category.</emphasis>
Based on estimates from GeoCAT, the EOO of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. kanayamaense" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="kanayamaense">
D. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
kanayamaense
</taxonomicName>
was 0.002 km2. AOO of 
<taxonomicName genus="D." lsidName="D. kanayamaense" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" rank="species" species="kanayamaense">
D. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
kanayamaense
</taxonomicName>
was 4.0 km2. There were only approximately 124 individuals in the type locality and the population size is not decreasing. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="PhytoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="39" refId="B7" refString="IUCN, 2012. Guidelines for application of IUCN Red List criteria at regional and national levels: Version 4.0. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK." title="Guidelines for application of IUCN Red List criteria at regional and national levels: Version 4.0. Gland, Switzerland and Cambridge, UK." year="2012">IUCN (2012)</bibRefCitation>
criteria, this hybrid is endangered (EN). A formal evaluation of endangerment can be summarised by the following IUCN hierarchical alphanumeric coding system of criteria: EN D.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
